y of AIDS drugs in the poorest countries, May and Sell present intellectual property law as a continuing process in which particular conceptions of rights and duties are institutionalized; each settlement prompts new disputes, policy shifts, and new disputes again. They also examine the post-TRIPs era in the context of this process. Their account of two thousand years of technological advances, legal innovation, and philosophical arguments about the character of knowledge production suggests that the future of intellectual property law will be as contested as its past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIntellectual propertyxHistory. 0aIntellectual propertyxPolitical aspects. 0aIntellectual propertyxSocial aspects. 0aPropriété intellectuellexAspect politique. 0aPropriété intellectuellexAspect social. 0aPropriété intellectuellexHistoire. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aMay, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSell, Susan K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078425140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978162637002940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781626370029423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781626370029/original  a978-3-11-078425-1  Lynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK